Grapevine leaf disease detection has seen significant advancements with the application of deep learning, machine learning, and spectroscopic approaches. CNN-based models dominate this field due to their superior ability to extract spatial features. For example, “A high-throughput ResNet CNN approach for automated grapevine leaf hair quantification” applied a ResNet model for hair quantification on grape leaves, achieving an accuracy of 95.41%. Segmentation of diseased regions has also been explored; “GMamba: State space model with convolution for Grape leaf disease segmentation” employed a UNet-based state-space model on PlantVillage data, achieving an IoU of 3.28. Object detection methods further facilitate practical field deployment: “Optimizing precision agriculture: A real-time detection approach for grape vineyard unhealthy leaves using deep learning improved YOLOv7 with feature extraction capabilities” achieved 64.6% mAP, while the YOLOv11-based approach in “Lightweight Grape Leaf Disease Identification for Complex Field Scenes: YOLO-Grape Model and Its Boundary-Lesion Coalesce Optimization Policies” reached 95.2% mAP.

High-performance classification has been demonstrated using various deep learning architectures. ResNet variants such as in “Precision detection of grapevine downy and powdery mildew diseased leaves and fruits using enhanced ResNet50 with batch normalization” achieved 95% accuracy. Multi-backbone fusion approaches like “AFC-Net: Attention-Guided Multi-backbone Deep Fusion for Grape Leaf Disease Classification” combining ResNet50, EfficientNetB0, and MobileNetV2 attained 99.83% accuracy. Hybrid models incorporating transformers, e.g., “Lightweight grape leaf disease recognition method based on transformer framework,” achieved 98.48% accuracy, while cascaded CNNs in “Artificial Intelligence Enabled Grape Leaf Disease Detection Model with Improved Cascaded Convolutional Neural Network” reached near-perfect classification (~100%). MobileNetV2 combined with ViT in “PCNN-Based Grape Leaf Disease Detection Using MobileNetV2 and ViT with XAI” achieved 99.2% accuracy. Comparative studies such as “A Comparative Deep Learning Framework for Grape Leaf Disease Classification Using EfficientNetB0, InceptionV3, and Xception” achieved 99.5% accuracy, while DCNNs based on VGG16 in “Multiclass classification of diseased grape leaf identification using deep convolutional neural network (DCNN) classifier” reached 99.18%. Optimized CNNs also performed strongly, as shown in “DeepLeaf: an optimized deep learning approach for automated recognition of grapevine leaf diseases” with 99.7% accuracy and “Enhancing agriculture through real-time grape leaf disease classification via an edge device with a lightweight CNN architecture and Grad-CAM” achieving 99.66%. Even simpler optimized CNN approaches, such as in “Disease Detection in Grape Leaves Using Convolutional Neural Networks,” demonstrated reliable performance.

Beyond classical CNNs, machine learning and spectroscopic approaches provide complementary insights. “AI-Driven Identification of Grapevine Fungal Spores via Microscopic Imaging and Feature Optimization with Cuckoo Search Algorithm” used SVM and feature optimization for fungal spore classification, reaching 97.5% accuracy. Chemometric regression models, such as in “Spectroscopic analysis (UV-VIS-NIR) for predictive modeling of macro and micronutrients in grapevine leaves,” enabled macro- and micronutrient prediction with an R² of 0.90 for sodium. Early viral detection was demonstrated using hyperspectral and multispectral sensing in “Identification of unique electromagnetic signatures from GLRaV-3 infected grapevine leaves in different stages of virus development,” detecting strong infections with CT < 35.

Collectively, these studies illustrate that advanced CNN architectures, hybrid transformer frameworks, multi-backbone fusion, and feature-based machine learning approaches provide robust and high-accuracy solutions for grape leaf disease detection, nutrient assessment, and pathogen monitoring. Real-time, edge-deployable, and spectroscopic methods further enhance precision viticulture by enabling timely interventions, improved crop management, and sustainable vineyard productivity.
